NASM diff√©rences with MASM 





Nasm literal variable name s



MASM: Uses the PTR keyword (e.g., BYTE PTR, DWORD PTR).

NASM: Does not use PTR; it just uses the size name.





NASM: section .data, section .text





Variable Declaration:

MASM: varname DWORD 10
NASM: varname dd 10 (Define Double)
If your book uses .model flat, stdcall, option casemap, or proto, ignore them. These are specific to Microsoft's linker and memory models. NASM on Linux relies on the standard ELF format.

/usr/bin/ld: warning: src/test.o: missing .note.GNU-stack section implies executable stack
/usr/bin/ld: NOTE: This behaviour is deprecated and will be removed in a future version of the linker
/usr/bin/ld: src/test.o: warning: relocation in read-only section `.text'
/usr/bin/ld: warning: creating DT_TEXTREL in a PIE



nasm -f elf64 program.asm -o program.o

Link: ld program.o -o program

Run: ./program



TOOLS 
constant defined as 
<name> eq <value> 

DATA SECTION 
<variable name >  <dataType> <initial value > 
db 8 bit 
dw 16bit 
dd 32 bits 
dq 64 bits 
ddq 128 bits 
dt -> float 


Examples oof constant and data sections which defines initialized vairaqble 
bVar db 10 ; byte variable 
cVar db "H" ; single character 
strng db "HELLO World" ; string 
wvar dw 5000 ; 16 bit variable 
dVar dd 500000 ; 32 bit varaible 
arr dd  100, 200 , 300 ; 3 elements in an array 
flt1 dd 3.14159 ; 32 bit float 
qVar dq 10000000000 ; 64 bit vairaible

BSS SECTION 
<vairable name > <restype> <count> 

unintialized data -> bss section 
resb -> 8bit 
resw -> 16 bit 
resd -> 32 bits 
resq -> 64 bits 
resdq -> 128 btis 

examples of reserve
bArr resb 10; 10 element byte arrays 
wArr resw 50 ; 50 word elemnet arraays 
dArr resd 100 ; 100 element double array 
qArr resq 200; 200 elemt of quad array ; 

.TEXT section 
this contains code of the executable file 
i.e global _start 
